[u], and [a]. E.g: [mili] means “more”, [mali] means “flood waters”, and [mulu] means “nose”,%0a%3c %0a%3c I think it’s fascinating that many Aboriginal Australian languages have very few vowel contrasts (and very few vowel sounds in general). It would be interesting to further investigate what sort of factors (geographical or cultural) may have resulted in this.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: http://sealang.net/archives/pl/pdf/PL-A37.1.pdf%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: :)%0a%3c (:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
